Rajju in the Rigveda^1 and later^2 denotes ‘rope.’ In the<BR>Atharvaveda^3 the serpent is called the ‘toothed rope’ (rajju<BR>datvatī).<BR>1) i. 162, 8 (śīrṣaṇyā raśanā rajjuḥ,<BR>referring to the horse presumably means<BR>the head harness).<BR>2) Av. iii. 11, 8; vi. 121, 2; Taittirīya<BR>Saṃhitā, ii. 5, 1, 7; Śatapatha Brāh-<BR>maṇa, i. 3, 1, 14; x. 2, 3, 8; xi. 3,<BR>1, 1, etc.<BR>3) iv. 3, 2; xix. 47, 7, 8; Bloomfield,<BR>Hymns of the Atharvaveda, 368.<BR><a href="https://yaahi.github.io/?cp=2-199&d=VEI" target="_blank">PDF</a><BR><a href="https://yaahi.github.io/?d=vei&e=2620" target="_blank">Correction</a>

