सुजात
Su-jāta, ‘well-born,’ is an epithet found applied to men in a<BR>few passages of the Rigveda. It would probably be a mistake<BR>to press the sense so as to denote ‘nobles’ as compared with<BR>the people. See Sabhā.<BR>^1 ii. 2, 11; v. 6, 2; vii. 1, 4. 15; viii. 20, 8.<BR><a href="https://yaahi.github.io/?cp=2-453&d=VEI" target="_blank">PDF</a><BR><a href="https://yaahi.github.io/?d=vei&e=3592" target="_blank">Correction</a>

सुतम्भर|सुतंभर
Sutaṃ-bhara is credited by the Anukramaṇī (Index) with<BR>the authorship of certain hymns of the Rigveda.^1 The word<BR>does not occur in those hymns, but it appears as an adjective<BR>(‘carrying away Soma’) elsewhere,^2 and may, in a second<BR>passage,^3 by a conjecture^4 be taken as a man's name.<BR>1) v. 11-14.<BR>2) v. 44, 13.<BR>3) ix. 6, 6.<BR>4) If sutaṃ-bharāya be read for sutdṃ<BR>bhárāya, as Roth suggests in the St.<BR>Petersburg Dictionary, s.v.<BR><a href="https://yaahi.github.io/?cp=2-453&d=VEI" target="_blank">PDF</a><BR><a href="https://yaahi.github.io/?d=vei&e=3593" target="_blank">Correction</a>

